docs.abstract: Some residents are living precariously on the edges of roads, uncertain about a post-earthquake future.
docs.snippet: Some residents are living precariously on the edges of roads, uncertain about a post-earthquake future.
docs.lead_paragraph: GUÁNICA, P.R. — It was the third interminable night living on the edge of a road in their wrecked Puerto Rico town, but this time the three boys huddled on an inflatable mattress had a welcome diversion: a flat-screen TV perched on milk crates that allowed them to play Mortal Kombat 11.

headline.main: The Puerto Rico Earthquake Was Three Days Ago. People Are Still Living Outdoors.
headline.print_headline: Seeking Refuge Wherever They Can Find It

docs.abstract: The move by the group of young climate activists was another sign that left-wing advocacy organizations have increasingly coalesced around the Vermont senator’s candidacy.
docs.snippet: The move by the group of young climate activists was another sign that left-wing advocacy organizations have increasingly coalesced around the Vermont senator’s candidacy.
docs.lead_paragraph: The Sunrise Movement, the collection of young climate activists who have roiled Capitol Hill and the Democratic presidential primary,  announced on Thursday that it was endorsing Senator Bernie Sanders of Vermont, in another sign that left-wing advocacy groups have increasingly coalesced around his candidacy.

headline.main: Bernie Sanders’s Latest Endorsement: Sunrise Movement
headline.print_headline: Sanders Gets Endorsement Of Young Climate Group, Bolstering Left-Wing Ties

docs.abstract: Immigration. Race. Demographic change. Political demagogy. That year’s presidential race had it all. What can it tell us about 2020?
docs.snippet: Immigration. Race. Demographic change. Political demagogy. That year’s presidential race had it all. What can it tell us about 2020?
docs.lead_paragraph: Can any past presidential campaign help us understand the election year now beginning? There never was a sitting president like Donald Trump. But if we widen our lens, we find timely echoes in an era when America was rapidly changing, the old political order was coming apart, and it seemed like the country was about to split at the seams.

docs.abstract: The fugitive auto executive, who has turned up in Beirut, said he fled Japan to avoid a cooked-up case against him.
docs.snippet: The fugitive auto executive, who has turned up in Beirut, said he fled Japan to avoid a cooked-up case against him.
docs.lead_paragraph: The latest episode in the long-running saga of Carlos Ghosn, his news conference in Beirut on Wednesday, was a fitting sequel to the drama of his arrest in Japan, his stints in jail and his made-for-TV flight concealed in a large trunk and accompanied by a former Green Beret. Longtime viewers will recall that in earlier seasons, Mr. Ghosn, the son of three continents, had leapfrogged across the globe to save two auto companies from ruin (or was it three?), had staged a fabulous wedding at the Palace of Versailles and had done feats too many to list.

docs.abstract: A protest over President Emmanuel Macron’s pension overhaul, now in its sixth week, is amplified by 200 years of French history.
docs.snippet: A protest over President Emmanuel Macron’s pension overhaul, now in its sixth week, is amplified by 200 years of French history.
docs.lead_paragraph: PARIS — A bright red tapestry featuring the Cuban revolutionary Che Guevara over the words “Onward toward victory!” exhorts strikers not to give up, in the union’s dingy local headquarters. Outside, the local’s boss shouted through a megaphone at the Gare de Lyon train station: “The rich should never forget: There will always be the sweat of the poor on their money!”

headline.main: At the Heart of France’s Long Strikes, a Fight Between the Haves and the Have-Nots
headline.print_headline: France’s Strikes Rage On, Amplified by History

docs.abstract: Walking a fine line on politics and free expression, the International Olympic Committee published guidelines for how competitors can make statements at the Tokyo Games.
docs.snippet: Walking a fine line on politics and free expression, the International Olympic Committee published guidelines for how competitors can make statements at the Tokyo Games.
docs.lead_paragraph: LAUSANNE, Switzerland — The International Olympic Committee is taking no chances. Amid an increase in athlete activism and rising political tensions worldwide, the organization has settled on strict — and specific — guidelines for the types of actions, gestures and statements competitors at this summer’s Tokyo Olympics will be permitted to make.

headline.main: Olympic Protest Rules: Tweets Are Fine, Kneeling Is Not
headline.print_headline: I.O.C. Sets Strict Rules for Protest in Tokyo
